nd":"Fife, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","Fifeshire Scotland":"Scotland","Balberton, Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland","Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirlingshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Arnot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Arnott  .","German: variant of   Arnold  . This surname is very rare in Germany. In North America, it may also be an altered form of the variant <b>Arnodt</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Arnott","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a place called Arnot in Portmoak, Kinross.","Scottish and English: variant of   Arnold  .","English: variant of   Arnett  ."]},{"name":"Jarnot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse.","Polish: from the personal name <i>Jarnot</i>, an adaptation of German   Arnot  . It occurs mainly in western part of Greater Poland and on the borderland of Silesia and Lesser Poland (the areas of old German settlement in Poland).","French: variant of   Garneau  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most 